aces with short factual copy (no confetti treatment).\n- Disabled states: lowered contrast plus explicit reason text under the control.\n- High-contrast fallback: swap to system semantic colors (`.label`, `.systemBackground`, `.systemRed`) and add 1px borders on key controls.\n\n## Typography\n- Dynamic Type: all mission-critical text scales through AX sizes; CTA containers grow vertically instead of truncating.\n- Roles:\n  - Title: wake status and phase label.\n  - Body: instructions and consequence text.\n  - Caption: timing detail and audit metadata.\n- Numeric treatment: tabular figures for countdowns, streak counts, and completion timestamps.\n- Minimum readable sizes: 17pt body baseline, 15pt secondary metadata, never below 13pt for tappable-context labels.\n\n## Motion\n- Transition principles: quick, directional, state-explaining transitions (arm -> active -> complete), not ornamental movement.\n- Reduce Motion: replace transforms with opacity swaps and static state banners.\n- Haptics: single medium impact on wake start, success notification on completion, warning notification on miss.\n- Timing ranges: 120-180ms micro state change, 220-320ms screen transition; avoid chained animations.\n- Wake-state restraint: suppress non-essential animation while task is active to reduce cognitive load.\n\n## Screen-By-Screen Implications\n- Onboarding: 3-step max; step 1 defines wake intent, step 2 sets minimum viable schedule, step 3 confirms. Skip-safe path allowed with default schedule and later edit.\n- Home: top module is \"Next Wake Mission\" with hard state label (`Armed`, `Due`, `Missed`, `Recovered`) and one primary action.\n- Primary list: tasks sorted by urgency first, then recency; each row shows state token and next trigger time.\n- Create/edit: progressive disclosure. Required fields first; advanced constraints hidden under \"Strict Options\".\n- Active task: full focus surface with one primary action, one fallback action, and persistent consequence/status line.\n- Completion: immediate factual summary (time, streak effect, next wake), then recovery options if partially failed.\n- History/streaks: emphasize reliability trend and miss-repair actions over badge collection.\n- Profile/settings: split sections into `Wake Operations`, `Preferences`, `Account & Legal`; dangerous actions isolated at bottom.\n- Paywall/subscription: shown after value proof moments (post-completion/history insight), never interrupting an active wake flow.\n\n## Monetization Implications\n- Premium promise: higher reliability tooling (advanced schedule rules, deeper reliability analytics, smart recovery suggestions).\n- Remain free: core wake/task loop (create, arm, complete, basic history, basic reminders).\n- Dark-pattern avoidance: no countdown pressure on paywall, no fake scarcity, no blocking dismissal during wake-critical paths.\n\n## Accessibility Risks\n- VoiceOver: dense wake UI can become verbose; custom rotor labels are needed for state, timer, and primary action.\n- Dynamic Type: compact urgent layout may clip metadata if component heights are fixed.\n- Contrast: urgent tints can reduce legibility in dark mode if red overlays are too saturated.\n- Reduced motion: state clarity may collapse if motion is removed without explicit textual transitions.\n- Haptics-only feedback: misses users with haptics disabled; all haptic events need mirrored visual/text feedback.\n- Cognitive load: hard-accountability tone can overwhelm if multiple warnings stack in active state.\n- One-handed use: top-heavy controls conflict with reachability; primary wake action should anchor in lower thumb zone.\n\n## Implementation Risks\n- SwiftUI complexity: custom token system + multi-state surfaces can fragment modifiers and increase regressions.\n- Custom component risk: reusable \"Wake State Banner\" and \"Urgent Action Card\" may require careful environment-driven theming.\n- Animation risk: state machine bugs likely if wake transitions are modeled ad hoc instead of explicit enum-driven flow.\n- App Store risk: over-aggressive urgency language or alarm-like coercion could be flagged as manipulative UX.\n- Localization risk: compact hard-tone copy may expand significantly in non-English locales and break hierarchy.\n- Scope tradeoffs: if time-constrained, prioritize active-task clarity and history explanations before visual polish.\n\n## Source List\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/design-opportunity-synthesis.md`: consolidated weaknesses/opportunities and evidence constraints.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/competitor-flows.md`: onboarding, tab clarity, urgent active-task pattern signals.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/app-store-review-mining.md`: evidence-gap handling and onboarding friction caution.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md`: fallback principles for calm setup, urgent execution, recovery.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/pageflows-research.md`: progressive onboarding and single-action urgent flow heuristics.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/apple-hig-research.md`: iOS-native accessibility and predictability constraints.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/behavioral-ux-research.md`: tone separation between setup and urgent execution.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json`: environment/network limits affecting evidence confidence.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json`: confirms prior research gaps and live-research dependency.\n\n## What To Adapt\n- Progressive disclosure for setup: intent first, strictness later.\n- Single dominant action during wake-critical moments.\n- Explicit state language (`Armed`, `Due`, `Missed`, `Recovered`) across home, active, and history.\n- Recovery-first completion framing with immediate retry/repair options.\n- Strong separation of mission-critical controls from account/legal settings.\n\n## What Not To Copy\n- Any competitor or library-specific layout composition, spacing blueprint, or visual motif.\n- Any proprietary screenshots, icon packs, brand palettes, or marketing copy.\n- Any distinctive gamification sequence, badge art, or celebratory animation cadence from third-party apps.\n- Any coercive monetization sequence that interrupts urgent wake execution.\n- Any unverified claims presented as factual review insights when evidence is source-limited.\n\n## No Secret Output\n- secret material omitted\nEOF'","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
